1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:27,000
[SPEAKER_00] Before we begin, a word about beards. In 2022, I published a book on beards, azymes, and purgatory: the other issues that divided East and West. While I was writing, many people asked me about the beard thing and whether it really was true that one of the reasons Catholics and Orthodox were separated had anything to do with beards. And I replied, "Well, it was featured in Humbert's Anathema as a reason for breaking Communion."

2
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] It was mentioned in the Greek Synod's response, and in Michael Corullius's letter to Peter of Antioch, and over half the list of Latin errors. So yes, it was a reason for breaking Communion. For the Byzantines, beardlessness manifested a clear Judaizing tendency within Latin Christianity, as well as a willingness to violate the apostolic institutions and the ancient canons of the undivided Church. Historically speaking, the fact that the Latins

3
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:09,000
[SPEAKER_00] were predominantly beardless, although there were occasional vagaries of fashion that allowed it to occasionally reappear. The Byzantine beard was, by the 7th to 8th centuries, ubiquitous, most likely grown by men as a way of distinguishing themselves from eunuchs.

4
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:36,000
[SPEAKER_00] Even Phocis mentioned the difference without attributing any significance to it, writing that some have the custom of cutting their hair and shaving, while to others, this is prohibited by certain conciliar decrees. Thus, he recognized that different customs and rules exist in different places, and that one should not condemn those who hold such rules themselves, nor those who have not accepted them.

5
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:51,000
[SPEAKER_00] As a result of Corby and Aeneas of Corby and Aeneas of Paris wrote elegant defenses of beardlessness, for the most part, the debate was forgotten until 1054, when Humbert wrote that the Greeks, quote, preserving their hair and beards, do not receive into communion those who,

6
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:55,000
[SPEAKER_00] according to the custom of the Roman Church, cut their hair and shave their beards.

7
00:01:55,000 --> 00:02:06,000
[SPEAKER_00] The response of the Greeks was that it was the Latins who were at fault, accusing us of refusing to shave our beards as they do, and to alter the natural human appearance.

8
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:19,000
[SPEAKER_00] Regardless of who first raised the issue, this seemingly insignificant cultural difference became one of the reasons both sides gave for breaking communion in 1054.

9
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:32,000
[SPEAKER_00] If one accepts Maximus the Confessor's letter to Marinus as authentic, and I would, then the dispute about the filioque might be among the oldest ongoing debates in Christendom.

10
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] There is little doubt that by the 7th century, Christian East and West had begun to speak about the procession of the Holy Spirit using different, although not necessarily contradictory, concepts and categories.

11
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:58,000
[SPEAKER_00] The Greek fathers, led by Basil the Great and Gregory Nazianzus, emphasized the notion that the hypostasis of the Father was defined by his unique role as unoriginate cause of the Son and the Spirit, the former by generation, the latter by procession.

12
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:17,000
[SPEAKER_00] While other fathers also spoke of the Spirit's eternal relationship to the Son, moving through him from the Father, the Greek tradition remained content, repeating the creedal affirmation of the Nicene-Constantinopolitan Creed, itself derived from Scripture, that the Holy Spirit proceeds from the Father.

13
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] However, among the Western fathers, especially those who wrote after Augustine, greater emphasis was placed on the Spirit's role as the mutual love proceeding from both Father and Son.

14
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:41,000
[SPEAKER_00] As the Aryan crisis continued, Latin authors felt it necessary to affirm that everything the Father has belongs also to the Son, including, so they believed, the ability to spirate the Holy Spirit.

15
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:55,000
[SPEAKER_00] For these reasons, by the 8th century, the filioque found itself inserted in the creed of several local councils in the West, with many authors simply assuming that the doctrine was both apostolic and ecumenical.

16
00:03:55,000 --> 00:04:09,000
[SPEAKER_00] Eager to contrast their orthodoxy with the faith of the allegedly heretical Byzantines, in the late 8th century, the Carolingians made the filioque a cornerstone of their anti-Aryan polemic.

17
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] The filioque became central to the Frankish faith, even if Rome remained more hesitant about altering the creed to allow its inclusion.

18
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:36,000
[SPEAKER_00] In fact, Pope Leo III famously went so far as to place two silver shields in Rome, containing the uninterpolated creed in both Greek and Latin, commanding the Franks to remove the filioque, and recommending that gradually the custom of singing the creed be dispensed with.

19
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:45,000
[SPEAKER_00] Undeterred, however, the Franks continued to profess the filioque, bringing their creed with them as they began preaching among the Bulgars.

20
00:04:45,000 --> 00:05:00,000
[SPEAKER_00] When Patriarch Phocius of Constantinople became aware of this novel teaching, he responded quickly, setting out his arguments against the filioque in his Mystagogia, which would become the basis for Orthodox objections for centuries to come.

21
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:17,000
[SPEAKER_00] Although a few voices in the West tried to reconcile the views of the two sides, by the time of the so-called Phocianism, and when it was resolved in 869, a clear dialectic had been established that would endure for the next several centuries.

22
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:26,000
[SPEAKER_00] Either the spirit proceeded from the father alone, as the East believed, or from the father and the son, as the West professed.

23
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:41,000
[SPEAKER_00] By 1014, the growing power of the Ottonians finally forced the Pope to accept the filioque in the creed at Rome, forever joining the legitimacy of the addition to the Pope's right to decide the faith of the universal church.

24
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] But here is the interesting thing.

25
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:51,000
[SPEAKER_00] Even after all this, the filioque and its place in the creed was not a cause of what happened in 1054.

26
00:05:51,000 --> 00:06:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] In fact, the matter never came up until Humbert's anathema, when he accused the Constantinopolitans of heresy by omitting it.

27
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:07,000
[SPEAKER_00] Patriarch Michael Corullius then quickly picked it up, calling it the artifice of the devil that must be condemned.

28
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:12,000
[SPEAKER_00] And he made it the chief theological issue in all the debates that followed.

29
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] The filioque had now become a casus belli, and the battle was joined.

30
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:26,000
[SPEAKER_00] So if the filioque was not the immediate cause of the schism between East and West, what was?

31
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:32,000
[SPEAKER_00] And that role is reserved for the Latin's use of unleavened bread, or azons, in the Eucharist.

32
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:52,000
[SPEAKER_00] When, in 1089, Pope Irvin II asked the Emperor Alexius I why his name was not included in the diptychs, the Emperor's response made no mention of the primacy or the procession, but rather spoke of that schism whereby the Greeks sacrificed with leavened bread while the Latins with unleavened.

33
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:59,000
[SPEAKER_00] Among the Byzantine's complaints was that the Latin practice was a novelty, and thus counter to the long-standing practice of the universal church.

34
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] And in this, they were probably correct, as it seems that the use of leavened bread throughout the West was normative until the 9th to 10th centuries.

35
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:13,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, the Roman justification for this new practice was largely based on a biblical argument.

36
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:24,000
[SPEAKER_00] According to the Synoptic Gospels, Matthew, Mark, and Luke, Jesus had celebrated the Last Supper as a Passover meal, and thus he would have used unleavened bread for the institution of the Eucharist.

37
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:29,000
[SPEAKER_00] The Church, at least the Roman Church, was simply acting in imitation of its Savior.

38
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:33,000
[SPEAKER_00] The Byzantine response was also based on biblical evidence.

39
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:51,000
[SPEAKER_00] According to the Gospel of John, whose chronology of Jesus' last days seemingly differed from the Synoptics, the Last Supper was not a Passover meal, which is why the Gospels and Paul talk about the bread being used that night as artos, or bread, rather than asimos, or unleavened bread.

40
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:57,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, naturally, there were other arguments against the Latin in practice, aside from its relative novelty.

41
00:07:57,000 --> 00:08:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] The fact that some of the Byzantine's neighbors, the Armenians, used azymes and were monophysites led the Byzantines to the conclusion that the Latins must also have embraced the same heresy.

42
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:16,000
[SPEAKER_00] Of course, the use of azymes by the Jews in the celebration of the Passover raised the charge that the Latins were again Judaizing,

43
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:23,000
[SPEAKER_00] Clinging to the rights of the old law, instead of embracing the life-giving sacrifice of the new.

44
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:29,000
[SPEAKER_00] It was this perceived connection between leaven and life that became the Byzantine's chief argument against azymes.

45
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:38,000
[SPEAKER_00] So that just as the body without breath is dead, matzah, which does not have leaven, is dead and is not a living loaf.

46
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:45,000
[SPEAKER_00] For the leaven gives life and oneness to the dough, just as spirit does to the body.

47
00:08:45,000 --> 00:09:00,000
[SPEAKER_00] This was actually the issue that had brought Humbert to Constantinople in the summer of 1054, as the attacks of Leo of Ovid and Nikitos Tethatos against the horrible infirmities of the Latin church demanded an answer.

48
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:06,000
[SPEAKER_00] One interesting feature of the entire Aesomite debate was how remarkably one-sided it was.

49
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:13,000
[SPEAKER_00] But while the Byzantines objected, often quite strenuously, to the Western practice of using unleavened bread,

50
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] the Latins never questioned the Eastern tradition and universally accepted the validity of the Greek sacrament using leavened bread.

51
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] It is true that Humbert thought the Greeks presumptuous for teaching the successor of St.

52
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:34,000
[SPEAKER_00] Peter how to offer the sacrifice and presumptuous for denying the validity of the Latin Eucharist.

53
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] And yet he and almost every other Latin who addressed the issue throughout the centuries did not respond by requiring the Greeks to adopt Aesoms.

54
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:56,000
[SPEAKER_00] Instead, they simply demanded that the Greek attacks against the Aesomites must stop and that the validity of the Latin practice be accepted by the Byzantines, just as the Greek practice was accepted by the West.

55
00:09:56,000 --> 00:10:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] Clerical celibacy

56
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:14,000
[SPEAKER_00] Although certain New Testament passages have been the focus of the debate on clerical celibacy, particularly Matthew 19:12, 1 Corinthians 7, and 1 Timothy 3:2,

57
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] the connection between sexual continence and cultic purity goes back to the Old Testament.

58
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:35,000
[SPEAKER_00] In ancient Judaism, it was a religious obligation for a man to marry and raise a family, even if temporary sexual abstinence for specific purposes, for example, holy wars or priestly service, was not unknown.

59
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] The priests of the Old Testament were explicitly commanded to avoid defilement through sexual contact with prostitutes or divorced women,

60
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:56,000
[SPEAKER_00] eventually leading to the understanding that they would, even if married, observe sexual abstinence during the times when they led worship and were in contact with the divine mystery.

61
00:10:56,000 --> 00:11:04,000
[SPEAKER_00] The degree to which this understanding influenced the later thinking of Christ, Paul, or the early church remains a point of debate.

62
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:13,000
[SPEAKER_00] The same is true of the practices of the Essenes, who may have embraced a celibate lifestyle or abstained from sex only for certain periods.

63
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] Paul's advice to remain as I am would be easier to understand if not for the fact that later in that same letter,

64
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] he asked about the right to be accompanied by a believing wife, as do the other apostles and the brothers of the Lord and Cephas.

65
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:41,000
[SPEAKER_00] And his admonition that bishops be the husband of one wife in 1 Timothy 3:2 remains among the most disputed passages in the history of the celibacy debate.

66
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:53,000
[SPEAKER_00] The father's commentaries on these passages were influenced by the rise of asceticism, the Christian attitude towards sex, and the increased premium placed on virginity in relation to marriage.

67
00:11:53,000 --> 00:12:06,000
[SPEAKER_00] Jovinian was condemned by three doctors of the church, Ambrose to Rome and Augustine, for making the outrageous and even heretical claim that celibate and married Christians were equal in God's sight.

68
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:15,000
[SPEAKER_00] Despite the value that the fathers placed on celibacy in both East and West, it was not a requirement of the priesthood during the church's first seven centuries.

69
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] The fathers knew that at least some of the apostles were married, and that this in no way made them less deserving of the call.

70
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] For despite their exceptional sanctity, they were men like us, married with a family.

71
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:44,000
[SPEAKER_00] However, when it came to the issue of sexual continence, by the fourth century, one can discern a growing consensus that ministers serving at the altar and lay people receiving the Eucharist should abstain from sex before doing so.

72
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:47,000
[SPEAKER_00] Purity, both physical and spiritual, was key.

73
00:12:47,000 --> 00:13:07,000
[SPEAKER_00] The debate, and it remains alive, is whether the fathers expected married ministers to remain permanently continent after ordination, as legislation in the West would mandate beginning at the end of the fourth century, or whether the ban on conjugal relations was only temporary, like that of the Levites in the Old Testament.

74
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:10,000
[SPEAKER_00] And this was the predominant Eastern view.

75
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:16,000
[SPEAKER_00] When one begins to examine the canons and practices of the early church, certain things become clear rather quickly.

76
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] The first is that there was widespread acceptance of the ordination of married men, and married clergy in greater or lesser numbers was a normal feature of life of the church.

77
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:40,000
[SPEAKER_00] The second is that by the early fourth century, we also begin to see the first canonical prohibitions against men entering into marriage once they had been ordained.

78
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:49,000
[SPEAKER_00] Traditionally, the point of division between East and West on the issue of celibacy has been understood to be the Council in Trullo in 691-92.

79
00:13:49,000 --> 00:14:04,000
[SPEAKER_00] Orthodox interpreters of the Council have stressed its conservative nature, and the fact that most of Prullo's canons, which forbids second marriages, marriage after ordination, and legislated the continents of bishops, coincided exactly with those of the Latin church.

80
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:21,000
[SPEAKER_00] The exception, however, was canon 13, which allowed that a presbyter, deacon, or subdeacon need not abstain from lawful intercourse with his own wife, which the Byzantines knew to be at odds with the current practice of the Roman church.

81
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:31,000
[SPEAKER_00] The Roman folks were infuriated by the Byzantines' presumption, and initially refused to approve Trullo's canons, although limited assent was eventually given.

82
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:40,000
[SPEAKER_00] Over the next few centuries, the policies of the two churches vis-à-vis sexual continence were not a source of conflict, and passed largely without comment.

83
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:50,000
[SPEAKER_00] Even when tensions arose during the so-called Phocianism, Phocius recognized it was perfectly fine that in Rome, one does not find lawfully married priests.

84
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:56,000
[SPEAKER_00] While we have accepted that those who have been married once can be elevated to the priesthood.

85
00:14:56,000 --> 00:15:09,000
[SPEAKER_00] In the West, the fact that the great majority of clergymen in the West from Gregory the Great to the 10th century were married men, although in theory, they and their wives were expected to abstain from all conjugal relations.

86
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] Yet, given this psychologically abnormal situation, it is not surprising that so few actually did, and that the law of continence remained pretty much a dead letter.

87
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] It was at this point that the move for reform began, first at Clooney and then spreading out from the monastic cloister into the wider world.

88
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:37,000
[SPEAKER_00] Monastic chastity became a goal toward which priests were to aspire, and it brought with it the permanent vowed chastity of the monks to the celebration of the sacraments.

89
00:15:37,000 --> 00:15:50,000
[SPEAKER_00] Of course, there was resistance, but still the popes were determined, and a series of laws issued by Leo the ninth, Nicholas the second, and Gregory the seventh, eventually signaled the death knell of a married clergy.

90
00:15:50,000 --> 00:16:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] Interesting, it was exactly at this moment that tensions between East and West arose over the Aesons, so that when Nikita Stethatos began writing about the Latins, their practice of dissolving the marriage of priests, he said, was against the apostolic canons, the councils of Gangra and Trullo.

91
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] Cardinal Humbert was ready to respond. He wrote that by allowing married priests, the Greeks permitted the unseemly practice of allowing the priest's hands to touch first his wife, and then the body of Christ.

92
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:33,000
[SPEAKER_00] For the Byzantines, it was the Latin prohibition against priestly marriage that led to impiety, including the divorce of lawful wives, increased concubinage, and worst of all, all sorts of sexual naughtiness.

93
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:37,000
[SPEAKER_00] The Primacy of Rome

94
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:45,000
[SPEAKER_00] Reading the exchanges of Cardinal Humbert and Michael Corullius in 1054, one finds all of these issues laid out and more.

95
00:16:45,000 --> 00:17:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] And yet surprising to many is the fact that neither document is the papacy mentioned as a divisive issue, despite the fact today it is thought to be the principal obstacle standing in the way of Catholicism's reconstituted unity with the Orthodox Church.

96
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:17,000
[SPEAKER_00] Simply put, debates about the source justification for and limits of the authority granted to the Bishop of Rome within the universal church were not the immediate cause of the so-called great schism that grew up between East and West.

97
00:17:17,000 --> 00:17:25,000
[SPEAKER_00] And yet to say that the papacy was not the cause of the great schism does not mean that it was not ultimately the reason behind it.

98
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:41,000
[SPEAKER_00] There had never been an universally accepted view of the papacy within the church, and the reality is that for much of the first millennium, a variety of positions on the Roman primacy existed side by side, albeit with occasional tensions.

99
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:49,000
[SPEAKER_00] However, by the 11th century, the chances of continual peaceful coexistence began decreasing exponentially.

100
00:17:49,000 --> 00:18:03,000
[SPEAKER_00] The chief reason for this was the Gregorian reform, which had emerged out of the chaos of the pornocracy that had brought the papacy into such disrepute in the 10th and 11th centuries.

101
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:11,000
[SPEAKER_00] The argument of the reformers was simple, and it was expressed by Pope Gregory the 7th with almost algebraic simplicity.

102
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:19,000
[SPEAKER_00] God's will was made known to the church, whose governance was accepted by St. Peter and then passed on to his successors.

103
00:18:19,000 --> 00:18:24,000
[SPEAKER_00] For this reason, to disobey the pope was to disobey God himself.

104
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:37,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, although one can question how revolutionary this line of thinking was in the context of Latin ecclesiology, there's little doubt that these claims were departure from the tradition as the East had hitherto understood it.

105
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:48,000
[SPEAKER_00] Even the language that the pope used to describe relations between Rome and the other seas began to change, and formally, fraternal language was replaced by paternal terms.

106
00:18:48,000 --> 00:18:57,000
[SPEAKER_00] Rome was no longer a sister church, but rather the mother of all churches, to whom other churches owed filial obedience.

107
00:18:57,000 --> 00:19:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] This is why, when the East began to denounce the pope's use of azymes as Judaic and his teaching on the filioque as heretical, the Latins knew there must be an immediate response.

108
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:14,000
[SPEAKER_00] But these criticisms undermine the very foundation upon which the reformed papacy was built.

109
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:23,000
[SPEAKER_00] That is that the pope, as successor of St. Peter, was the rock to whom Christ entrusted both the church and the preservation of its teaching.

110
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:41,000
[SPEAKER_00] Thus, while the primacy of Rome does not explicitly appear as a divisive issue until much later, in attacking the theology behind the filioque, azymes, clerical celibacy, all of which had been embraced or defended by the popes, the East was challenging the papacy itself.

111
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:53,000
[SPEAKER_00] The Pope's orthodoxy and his authority were inherently linked, and if the Byzantines had not yet realized that, by 1054, Rome surely had.

112
00:19:53,000 --> 00:19:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] Conclusion.

113
00:19:54,000 --> 00:20:12,000
[SPEAKER_00] Although East-West theological exchanges were rare in the years that preceded the dialogue of love that began between Constantinople and Rome in the mid-20th century, the last 60 years or so have seen great advances made in resolving the issues that once divided the churches.

114
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:29,000
[SPEAKER_00] Today, many Catholic and Orthodox scholars believe the debate about the spirit procession may not be the insurmountable obstacle to unity it once was, with the majority of Catholic theologians urging that the filioque be dropped from the creed as an act of reconciliation.

115
00:20:29,000 --> 00:20:40,000
[SPEAKER_00] That is hard to find many Orthodox theologians still worked up over azymes or beards, and the debate over celibacy is more an eternal Roman Catholic issue than an ecumenical one.

116
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:53,000
[SPEAKER_00] Recent dialogues on the papacy, especially those held at Ravenna and Citi, have moved both sides closer to understanding the roots of Rome's primacy and the power or authority attached to it.

117
00:20:53,000 --> 00:21:04,000
[SPEAKER_00] Even if some very important differences remain, especially as it pertains to the teachings of Pastor Eternus on the universal jurisdiction and infallibility of the Pope.

118
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] The debates that shaped medieval Byzantine-Latin interactions still shape the churches today, although perhaps the modern context offers more hope for their resolution than was possible in the summer of 1054.

119
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:21,000
[SPEAKER_00] Thank you.

